</span>
</span></p><h2>Steamed Artichoke Serving Suggestions</h2><p>So, you learned how to cook artichokes&#8230;but what about how to <em>eat </em>them?</p><p>Steamed artichokes have three edible parts: the leaves, the stem, and the heart. To eat the leaves, you&#8217;ll peel them off one by one and scrape off the tender meat with your teeth, discarding the tough, fibrous shell. They&#8217;re tasty on their own, but they&#8217;re really not complete without some sort of dipping sauce. Melted butter is a classic choice, and creamy sauces are also delicious. Try serving them with <a
href=https://www.loveandlemons.com/caesar-dressing/ >Caesar dressing</a> or <a
href=https://www.loveandlemons.com/tartar-sauce/ >tartar sauce</a>.</p><p>Once you eat the leaves, you&#8217;ll be left with the cup-shaped artichoke heart and the stem. They&#8217;re meaty and flavorful &#8211; enjoy them with olive oil, sea salt, and lemon juice, or dip them in whatever sauce you served with the leaves.</p><p>Steamed artichokes are a wonderful appetizer for spring recipes like this <a
href=https://www.loveandlemons.com/tagliatelle/ >Tagliatelle with Asparagus and Peas</a>, <a
href=https://www.loveandlemons.com/pesto-pasta/ >Pesto Pasta</a>, or <a
href=https://www.loveandlemons.com/spaghetti-aglio-e-olio/ >Spaghetti Aglio e Olio</a>. They make a great side dish, too. Pair them with my <a
href=https://www.loveandlemons.com/asparagus-soup/ >Asparagus Soup</a> or any protein you like. Enjoy!</p><p>
